istian church, he explains, was one not of obliteration but of widening embrace and assimilation. This fascinating book also includes new material on the Christian persecution of pagans over the centuries through methods that ranged from fines to crucifixion; the mixture of motives in conversion; the stubbornness of pagan resistance; the difficulty of satisfying the demands and expectations of new converts; and the degree of assimilation of Christianity to paganism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChristianity and culturexHistoryxEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aChristianity and culturexHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aChristianity and other religionsxRoman. 0aChurch historyxPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aEvangelistic workxHistoryxEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aEvangelistic workxHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aPaganismxRelationsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300147544423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300147544.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles